  "slug": "topside-roast",
  "title": "Topside Roast",
  "subtitle": "A lean Sunday joint cooked low and slow for easy carving",
  "excerpt": "Topside is the leaner alternative to rib and sirloin: tighter-grained, more economical, and forgiving if you pull it slightly past medium. Cooked low and slow with a vegetable trivet, then rested generously, it carves cleanly and makes an excellent base for leftovers.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: topside preparation and boiling methods. Jane Grigson, English Food (1974): lean beef roasting notes. Traditional British home-cooking practice, cross-referenced across period sources.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Topside is the joint that rewards the economical cook. Cheaper than fore rib or sirloin, it still delivers a satisfying Sunday lunch when treated correctly: low heat, a good thermometer, and a proper rest. The tighter grain means it carves beautifully into thin, even slices, and any leftover beef makes excellent sandwiches the next day.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Unlike the fattier rib, ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "topside",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr2lzv0000lsv4fgz2tb6y"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " dries quickly if overcooked. Pull it at 60°C internal for a rosy-pink result, 65°C for medium. Anything beyond 70°C and the texture loses its appeal. The joint weighs roughly 1.5 kg for six servings; allow about 15 minutes per 500 g at 160°C after a short initial blast.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
