      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the trivet and seal the joint",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 220°C (200°C fan). Pat the joint dry with kitchen paper. Rub with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", then press ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " over all surfaces. Arrange the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{onion}} halved onions",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{carrot}} halved carrots",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", celery, and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{thyme}} of thyme",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in the roasting pan as a ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "trivet",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr2m0x0001lsv4lbel2tpt"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ". Set the joint on top and roast for 20 minutes to colour the outside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Slow roast to temperature",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Drop the oven to 160°C (140°C fan). Roast until the centre reaches 60°C for pink-and-juicy or 65°C for medium, probing away from any connective tissue seams. Start checking after 45 minutes and probe every 10 minutes thereafter.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest and make gravy",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lift the joint to a warm board, cover loosely with foil, and rest for 30 minutes. Pour off excess fat from the roasting pan, leaving the vegetables and any dark fond. Set over medium heat, add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{red-wine}} of red wine",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " if using, and scrape up the sediment. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of beef stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and simmer until reduced by a third. Strain into a warm jug before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Use a thermometer and check early. Topside dries out quickly past medium. Slicing thin and serving with plenty of gravy helps rescue an overcooked joint.",
              "cause": "Joint cooked past 70°C internal",
              "symptom": "Slices are dry and grey rather than pink"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Always rest at room temperature for at least 1 hour before cooking. Rotating the pan halfway through helps with oven hot spots.",
              "cause": "Joint was very cold when it went in, or oven has hot spots",
              "symptom": "The joint is unevenly cooked, well done at the ends and rare in the middle"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Snip and remove the strings before resting. The joint will hold its shape.",
              "cause": "Tied too tightly or meat swelled more than expected",
              "symptom": "The string is cutting into the meat"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Let the roasting pan sit over high heat for 2 minutes before adding liquid to deepen the colour.",
              "cause": "Trivet vegetables did not caramelise enough",
              "symptom": "Gravy is too pale"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Topside has been the thrifty Sunday joint of British households for generations. Where the rib is a show-off cut, topside is the workhorse: good on the day, better cold the next day in a sandwich with mustard and horseradish. Serve with roast potatoes, seasonal greens, and the gravy from the pan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
